without discontinuity. The jelly has had no way of ' knowing ' that the liquid within its meshes has become a gas. All that remains is to allow the gas to escape, and there is left behind a coherent aerogel of unchanged volume. Silica aerogel with a density so low as 0·1 is very easy to prepare, and we have prepared some with a density of only 0·02. The silica aerogels are highly opalescent, although quite transparent ; they display a glassy fracture and small pieces emit a metallic ring when dropped. So far, we have prepared silica, alumina, nickel tartarate, stannic oxide, tungstic oxide, gelatine, agar, nitrocellulose, cellulose, and egg albumin aerogels and see no reason why this list may not be extended indefinitely. Apart from the scientific significance of these observations, the new physical properties developed in the materials are of unusual interest.
